<h3 class="header"><i>1.3</i>Section 2.3<a class="headerlink" href="#section-23" name="section-23">&para;</a></h3>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.1</i>Question 1<a class="headerlink" href="#question-1_2" name="question-1_2">&para;</a></h4>
<blockquote>
<p>Let <span>$S_1 = \{x \in \mathbb R: x \geq 0\}$</span>. Show in detail that the set <span>$S_1$</span> has lower bounds, but no upper bounds. Show that <span>$\inf S_1 = 0$</span>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>No upper bound by the Archimedean property. 0 is a lower bound, and if <span>$w$</span> is any lower bound, we know that <span>$w \leq 0$</span> because 0 is in the set. Thus the infimum is 0.</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.2</i>Question 2<a class="headerlink" href="#question-2_2" name="question-2_2">&para;</a></h4>
<p>Skip</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.3</i>Question 3<a class="headerlink" href="#question-3_2" name="question-3_2">&para;</a></h4>
<blockquote>
<p>Let <span>$S_3 = \{1/n: n\in \mathbb N\}$</span>. Show that <span>$\sup S_3 = 1$</span> and <span>$\inf S_3 \geq 0$</span>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Coming soon</p>
<h4 class="header"><i>1.3.4</i>Question 4<a class="headerlink" href="#question-4_2" name="question-4_2">&para;</a></h4>
<blockquote>
<p>Let <span>$S_4 = \{1-(-1)^n/n:n \in \mathbb N\}$</span>. Find <span>$\inf S_4$</span> and <span>$\sup S_4$</span>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>First few terms: <span>$1-(-1)/1 = 2$</span>, <span>$1 - (1)/2 = 1/2$</span>, <span>$1 - (-1)/3 = 4/3$</span>, <span>$1 - (1)/4 = 3/4$</span>. So the inf is <span>$1/2$</span>, the sup is 2.</p>
