<h4 class="header"><i>2.1.1</i>Question 1<a class="headerlink" href="#question-1_5" name="question-1_5">&para;</a></h4>
<blockquote>
<p>The sequence <span>$(x_n)$</span> is defined by the following formulas for the <span>$n$</span>th term. Write the first five terms in each case:</p>
<p>(a) <span>$x_n = 1 + (-1)^n$</span>,<br />
(b) <span>$x_n = (-1)^n/n$</span>,<br />
(c) <span>$\displaystyle x_n = \frac{1}{n(n+1)}$</span>,<br />
(d) <span>$\displaystyle x_n = \frac{1}{n^2+2}$</span>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>(a) <span>$(0, 2, 0, 2, 0)$</span><br />
(b) <span>$(-1, 1/2, -1/3, 1/4, -1/5)$</span><br />
(c) <span>$(1/2, 1/6, 1/12, 1/20, 1/30)$</span><br />
(d) <span>$(1/3, 1/6, 1/11, 1/18, 1/27)$</span></p>
<h4 class="header"><i>2.1.2</i>Question 2<a class="headerlink" href="#question-2_5" name="question-2_5">&para;</a></h4>
<blockquote>
<p>The first few terms of a sequence <span>$(x_n)$</span> are given below. Assuming that the "natural pattern" indicated by these terms persists, give a formula for the <span>$n$</span>th term <span>$x_n$</span>.</p>
<p>(a) <span>$5, 7, 9, 11, \ldots$</span>,<br />
(b) <span>$/1/2, -1/4, 1/8, -1/16, \ldots$</span>,<br />
(c) <span>$1/2, 2/3, 3/4, 4/5, \ldots$</span>,<br />
(d) <span>$1, 4, 9, 16, \ldots$</span>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>(a) <span>$3 + 2n$</span><br />
(b) <span>$(-1)^{n+1}/2^n$</span><br />
(c) <span>$n/(n+1)$</span><br />
(d) <span>$n^2$</span></p>
